  1. Generate a dataset of 100,000 observations from this DGP. Call this the “population data”
x <- rnorm(100000, 10, 10)
u <- rnorm(100000, 0, 5)
y = 2.5 + 1.5 * x + u
population_data <- data.frame(x, u, y)
  1. Draw a random sample of 1,000 observations from the population data. Estimate the parameters \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\).
randX1000 <- sample_n(population_data, 1000)
randX1000Reg <- lm(formula = y ~ x, data = randX1000)
summary(randX1000Reg)

  1. Repeat step ii. 1000 times, and save the estimated parameters from each draw
beta_0_vector <- c()
beta_1_vector <- c()
for(i in 1:1000) {
  newPop <- population_data[sample(nrow(population_data), 1000), ]
  beta_0 <- mean(newPop$y) - mean(newPop$x) * beta_1
  beta_1 <- cov(newPop$y, newPop$x) / var(newPop$x)
  beta_0_vector <- c(beta_0_vector, beta_0)
  beta_1_vector <- c(beta_1_vector, beta_1)
}
  1. Present histograms of the sampling distribution of the estimates of \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\). Call these Figures 1 and 2 (with appropriate titles).
hist(beta_0_vector, main = "Figure 1", xlab = "beta_0", breaks = 30)

hist(beta_1_vector, main = "Figure 2", xlab = "beta_1", breaks = 30)

  1. What happens to the sampling distributions of the estimate of \(\beta_1\) if U ~ N(0, 50) or U ~ N(0, 1)? Present two more histograms, Figures 3 and 4.
x1 <- rnorm(100000, 10, 10)
u1 <- rnorm(100000, 0, 50)
y1 = 2.5 + 1.5 * x + u
situation_1 <- data.frame(x1, u1, y1)
beta_1_vector1 <- c()
for(i in 1:1000) {
  newPop1 <- situation_1[sample(nrow(situation_1), 1000), ]
  beta_1_1 <- cov(newPop1$y, newPop1$x) / var(newPop1$x)
  beta_1_vector1 <- c(beta_1_vector1, beta_1_1)
}
hist(beta_1_vector1, main = "Figure 3", xlab = "beta_1_1", breaks = 30)

x2 <- rnorm(100000, 10, 10)
u2 <- rnorm(100000, 0, 1)
y2 = 2.5 + 1.5 * x + u
situation_2 <- data.frame(x2, u2, y2)
beta_1_vector2 <- c()
for(i in 1:1000) {
  newPop2 <- situation_2[sample(nrow(situation_2), 1000), ]
  beta_1_2 <- cov(newPop2$y, newPop2$x) / var(newPop2$x)
  beta_1_vector2 <- c(beta_1_vector2, beta_1_2)
}
hist(beta_1_vector2, main = "Figure 4", xlab = "beta_1_2", breaks = 30)

The value of \(\beta_1\) in specification 2 is 0.093168, and that in specification 5 is 0.0800631. The proportion of difference between these two values is 14.0659424%. The value of \(\beta_2\) in specification 2 is 0.0406574, and that in specification 5 is 0.079552. The proportion of increase between these two variables is -95.664462%. The change in \(\beta_2\) is very siginificant.

In specification 2, if a worker gains one more year of experience, the increase in wage is e^0.0406574 unit. In specification 3, if a worker gains one more year of experience, the increase in wage is (e^0.0897828 + (e^(-0.0024859*exper))) unit.

(sum(res_5))
## [1] -1.438222

Properties of OLS estimatior (1 and 2): 1. The estimators for each indipendent variables are linear. 2. The OLS estimators are unbiased. In specification 1, all parameters are linear, therefore OLS property 1 holds. In specification 5, all parameters are linear as well, therefore OLS property 1 holds. The residual in specification 1 is -2.158273610^{-13}, and the residual in specification 5 is -2.158273610^{-13}. Neither residuals is zero. The one of specification 1 is very close to zero, but the one of specificaiton 5, compared to that in specification 1, is not very close to zero. Therefore, the estimators for specification 5 is biased.
